<body>

<h1>CHAPTER 4: SYSTEM IMPLEMENTATION AND TESTING</h1>

<h2>4.1 Technologies and Tools Used</h2>
<p>The KaviCakes Management System is a complete software solution built with three main parts: the Admin Web Dashboard, the Customer Web Portal, and a central API Backend. Both web platforms talk to the same backend server. This ensures that all business rules, prices, and security checks are controlled in one safe place before any data is updated or saved to the database.</p>
<p>The production system utilizes a localized storage architecture for operational files. For example, when a customer uploads a deposit slip to prove they made a payment, the image is saved directly into a local folder on the server. However, older product images that do not change often are safely stored in a cloud service called Supabase. The backend connects securely to a MySQL relational database to maintain data persistence. This means that customer accounts, order histories, and financial records are all linked together using strict relational rules to prevent data loss or mismatching records.</p>
<p>Because the system separates the frontend view from the backend logic, an administrator using a desktop computer and a customer using a smartphone will both experience smooth and fast loading times. The backend is designed only to process data in the form of JSON packages, which makes communication between the server and the browser incredibly fast and lightweight.</p>

<h2>4.2 Programming Languages and Development Tools</h2>

<h3>4.2.1 Backend — Node.js and Express.js</h3>
<p>The API is built using Node.js and the Express.js framework. This setup was chosen because it uses a non-blocking input/output model. This means the server can process a high number of customer orders at the exact same time without slowing down or crashing during busy holiday seasons. The database is managed using Prisma ORM. Prisma is a development tool that links the database directly to the code. It checks the data types before saving, ensuring that a phone number cannot accidentally be saved as a text word, which prevents errors.</p>
<p>Passwords are secured using a strong encryption tool called Bcryptjs with 10 salt rounds. This means the original text password is completely scrambled and turned into a random string of characters. Passwords are never saved as normal text anywhere in the system. The system also uses JSON Web Tokens (JWT) to keep users securely logged in without needing the server to manually remember their session every time they refresh the page. OTP codes for account activation are generated dynamically as 6-digit random numbers, and a background rule ensures they expire exactly after 10 minutes for safety.</p>

<h3>4.2.2 Admin Web — React and Vite</h3>
<p>The Admin Dashboard is a Single Page Application built with React, and it is bundled using Vite for faster development performance and smaller file sizes when published. The user interface is built heavily relying on Ant Design. Ant Design provides readymade, professional design components like interactive tables, input forms, off-canvas side drawers, and standardized date pickers. This allows the admin to filter and search through hundreds of orders quickly without the website freezing.</p>

<h3>4.2.3 Customer Web — React and Tailwind CSS</h3>
<p>The Customer Web Portal is also built using React, but its design is styled entirely using Tailwind CSS. Tailwind CSS uses small utility classes inside the code, which allows the developer to create a highly customized, colorful, and mobile-friendly boutique aesthetic that looks very different from the strict administrative interface. The website layout resizes properly whether the user is on a large monitor or a small smartphone screen. The Context API manages global states smoothly for the shopping cart and active login sessions.</p>

<h2>4.3 User Interfaces and Interaction Flow</h2>
<p>This section provides a comprehensive overview of the system interfaces. It defines the specific capabilities assigned to the Customer and Administrator, details the digital interactions between the two roles, and outlines the exact step-by-step lifecycle flow of a system order.</p>

<h3>4.3.1 What Can the Customer Do? (Customer Web Portal)</h3>
<p>The Customer Web Portal offers a frictionless ordering experience while strictly enforcing business rules in the background. A user logged into the system as a `CUSTOMER` has the following capabilities:</p>

<h4>4.3.1.1 Secure Account Management</h4>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Register and Verify:</strong> Customers can create an account by providing basic details. They must verify their email address by entering a 6-digit OTP (One-Time Password) before the system allows them to log in.</li>
    <li><strong>Profile Updates:</strong> Customers can update their personal information, save default delivery addresses, and view their currently accumulated Loyalty Points balance.</li>
</ul>

<h4>4.3.1.2 Browse and Search the Catalog</h4>
<ul>
    <li><strong>View Promotions:</strong> Customers land on a home screen displaying large hero banners and an algorithm-sorted "Best Sellers" section based on popular demand.</li>
    <li><strong>Filter and Search:</strong> They can filter cakes by specific categories (e.g., Birthday, Wedding) and use a live search bar to type and instantly find a specific cake by name.</li>
</ul>
<span class="image-message">[Insert Image: Customer Home screen and Searchable Product Catalog]</span>

<h4>4.3.1.3 Dynamic Cake Customization</h4>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Select Variants:</strong> Customers cannot just click "Buy." They must select their required Cake Size, Shape, and Flavor. The system immediately calculates and updates the price on the screen based on their specific combination.</li>
    <li><strong>Check Availability:</strong> If a specific size or flavor is out of stock, the customer will see it disabled and cannot add it to their cart.</li>
</ul>
<span class="image-message">[Insert Image: Single Product View with Variant Customization]</span>

<h4>4.3.1.4 Smart Checkout and Payments</h4>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Redeem Loyalty Points:</strong> During checkout, customers can use a slider to apply their earned Loyalty Points for a discount. The system automatically stops them from discounting more than 30% of the total cart value.</li>
    <li><strong>Choose Payment Method:</strong> Customers can choose "Online Payment" (requiring full immediate payment) or "Cash on Delivery" (COD).</li>
    <li><strong>Upload Bank Slips:</strong> If COD is selected, the system asks the customer to upload a photo of the bank transfer slip proving they have paid the mandatory 30% advance deposit.</li>
</ul>
<span class="image-message">[Insert Image: Shopping Cart Checkout showing the Payment Option and Loyalty Slider]</span>

<h4>4.3.1.5 Three-Tiered Ordering Capabilities (Standard, Custom, Bulk)</h4>
<p>The system empowers the customer to place three distinct types of orders, each possessing specialized user interfaces and pricing rules:</p>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Standard Orders:</strong> Direct selection from the predefined catalog menus. The system handles standard variant modifications (e.g., changing standard chocolate to vanilla) and processes immediate visual pricing on the screen before the customer proceeds to checkout.</li>
    <li><strong>Custom Design Orders:</strong> Customers can submit specialized requests for entirely unique cakes that are not listed on the standard menu. The dedicated interface provides advanced tools allowing the user to type explicit dietary notes, event themes, and upload visual reference images of their desired designs directly to the admin for review.</li>
    <li><strong>Bulk Event Orders:</strong> A specialized feature built specifically for corporate events or large weddings. Customers input high-volume quantities (e.g., 50+ boxes of cupcakes). The interface automatically intercepts standard pricing mechanics and dynamically applies specialized "Threshold Bulk Discounts," significantly reducing the per-unit cost based on the total quantity requested.</li>
</ul>

<h4>4.3.1.6 Order Tracking</h4>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Track Live Orders:</strong> Customers can access a timeline tracker that shows exactly what stage their order is in (e.g., Confirmed, Preparing, Ready) without needing to contact the shop directly.</li>
</ul>
<span class="image-message">[Insert Image: Timeline Order Tracker visualizing preparation stages]</span>

<h3>4.3.2 What Can the Admin Do? (Admin Control Center)</h3>
<p>The Admin dashboard is built for high-density data management. It hides promotional graphics in favor of tables, charts, and verification queues. A user logged in as an `ADMIN` has full structural control over the business operations.</p>

<h4>4.3.2.1 Business Analytics and Oversight</h4>
<ul>
    <li><strong>View Live KPIs:</strong> Automatically view today's active orders, the total pending advance payments, and graphical charts showing revenue trends over the month.</li>
</ul>
<span class="image-message">[Insert Image: Admin Dashboard Overview displaying Graphical Data Charts]</span>

<h4>4.3.2.2 Total Inventory Control</h4>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Manage Base Categories and Cakes:</strong> The admin can add new categories, create new cakes, and upload their respective images.</li>
    <li><strong>Configure Variant Pricing:</strong> Using dynamic forms, the admin can add an unlimited combination of sizes and flavors for a single cake, explicitly setting exactly how much each specific variant costs.</li>
</ul>

<h4>4.3.2.3 Comprehensive Order Management (Sub-Pages)</h4>
<p>The core order management module is logically divided into highly distinct sub-pages to maintain extreme operational organization. The admin maneuvers through the following specific queues to process daily operations efficiently:</p>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Standard Queue Panel:</strong> Monitors general catalog orders placed through the standard e-commerce menu. Admins can quickly transition simple cakes toward the "Preparing" phase and oversee daily retail order flows smoothly.</li>
    <li><strong>Custom & Bulk Action Array:</strong> A dedicated queue isolating highly complex orders. Here, admins specifically evaluate customer-uploaded reference images, confirm sufficient bulk inventory availability, and review special event dates due to the high resource requirements of these tasks.</li>
    <li><strong>Payment Verification Desk:</strong> A specialized sub-panel displaying exclusively orders resting in the <i>PENDING_VERIFICATION</i> state. This is where admins strictly examine uploaded bank transfer slip images side-by-side with the required 30% advance deposit targets. Only by manually clicking "Approve" here will an order unlock for preparation.</li>
    <li><strong>Order History & Archiving:</strong> A deeply searchable archive database isolating all <i>DELIVERED</i> and <i>REJECTED</i> customer profiles. This allows admins to retrieve old customer invoices or review historical cake modifications instantaneously.</li>
</ul>
<span class="image-message">[Insert Image: Admin Order Queue Table and Order Detail Action Drawer]</span>

<h4>4.3.2.4 Advanced Administration Features</h4>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Generate PDF Invoices:</strong> Admins can click a single button inside any order panel to generate a clean, professional PDF billing invoice automatically.</li>
    <li><strong>Automated Cashbook:</strong> Admins can view the daily cash ledger. The system automatically records the day's total online system income and calculates the exact daily Closing Balance. Admins can strictly log manual cash expenses within this view.</li>
    <li><strong>Edit Email Templates:</strong> Admins can edit the HTML text of the automated emails (like the "Order Ready" email) that the system sends out or trigger mass manual notifications targeting specific customer groups.</li>
</ul>

<h3>4.3.3 Interactions Between Admin and Customer</h3>
<p>The system is specifically designed so that the Customer and Admin do not need to call or text each other constantly. The platform handles interactions asynchronously through digital boundaries.</p>

<div class="flow-box">
    <strong>Action: Payment Verification Loop</strong><br>
    <span class="actor">Customer:</span> Uploads a photo of their bank deposit slip and clicks submit.<br>
    <span class="actor">System:</span> Changes the order status to `PENDING_VERIFICATION` immediately.<br>
    <span class="actor">Admin:</span> Sees the new order highlighted in the Verification Queue, opens the slip image, and clicks "Approve".<br>
    <span class="actor">System:</span> Secures the payment mathematically, allowing the order to move to the kitchen.
</div>

<div class="flow-box">
    <strong>Action: Real-Time Status Synchronization</strong><br>
    <span class="actor">Admin:</span> The baker finishes the cake. The admin logs in and clicks the "Mark as Ready" button.<br>
    <span class="actor">System:</span> Automatically sends an email ("Your Cake is Ready for Pickup!") to the customer's inbox.<br>
    <span class="actor">Customer:</span> Checks the "Track Order" page on their phone and instantly sees the graphic timeline light up on the "READY" stage.
</div>

<div class="flow-box">
    <strong>Action: Automated Urgency Warnings</strong><br>
    <span class="actor">Customer:</span> Places a highly custom order.<br>
    <span class="actor">System (Node-Cron):</span> Detects that the delivery date is less than 48 hours away. It automatically emails a "Final Warning" to the customer stating that no more design changes can be made.<br>
    <span class="actor">Admin:</span> Sees an "Urgent" flag applied to the order on the Standard Queue dashboard, prioritizing it in the kitchen.
</div>

<h3>4.3.4 The End-to-End Order Flow (Clear Step-by-Step)</h3>
<p>The following sequence represents the strictest, most complete lifecycle of a standard KaviCakes order, illustrating exactly how the backend business rules guard the process across both user interfaces.</p>

<ol>
    <li><p><strong>Phase 1: Catalog Selection [Customer Side]:</strong> The customer logs securely into the Web Portal. They browse the catalog, click on a specific cake, and select a variant (e.g. 2kg size, Chocolate flavor). The portal live-calculates the final price and the customer clicks "Add to Cart".</p></li>
    <li><p><strong>Phase 2: Checkout and Payment Gate [Customer Side]:</strong> The customer enters their delivery address and requests a specific delivery date. They choose to use Loyalty Points, reducing their bill slightly. Selecting "Cash on Delivery" triggers a visual warning that a 30% advance is required. The customer uploads a photo of their bank transfer receipt and clicks "Confirm Order".</p></li>
    <li><p><strong>Phase 3: Administrative Acknowledgment [Admin Side]:</strong> The order appears in the Admin Dashboard Order Table under the <i>NEW</i> status category. The Admin assesses the flavor variants and the requested delivery date, then clicks "Acknowledge Order", moving the status to <i>CONFIRMED</i>. The system sends an automated "Order Confirmed" email.</p></li>
    <li><p><strong>Phase 4: The Preparation Guardrail [System & Admin Side]:</strong> The Admin attempts to click "Begin Preparing." <strong>System Guardrail:</strong> The backend blocks the action because the 30% advance payment has not yet been manually verified. The Admin navigates to the Payment Verification Desk, views the uploaded bank slip, and clicks "Verify Advance Payment". With the payment officially verified, the admin clicks "Begin Preparing" successfully.</p></li>
    <li><p><strong>Phase 5: Finalization and Notification [Admin to Customer]:</strong> The physical cake is finished by the kitchen staff. The Admin clicks "Mark as Ready". The System automatically triggers Nodemailer to send a "Ready for Delivery/Pickup" email perfectly formatted to the Customer. The Customer logs into their portal and sees their timeline is updated.</p></li>
    <li><p><strong>Phase 6: Delivery and Financial Closure [Admin Side]:</strong> The cake is handed over and balance cash is collected. The Admin clicks "Mark as Delivered" and enters the balance collected as "In-Person Cash". <strong>System Closure:</strong> The order shifts to <i>DELIVERED</i>. A final PDF Invoice is emailed to the customer. At midnight, the total fully paid amount is securely transferred into the Daily Cashbook ledger as system Income.</p></li>
</ol>

<h2>4.4 Quality Assurance Methods Used</h2>
<p>Quality assurance and testing were conducted continuously to ensure the application could not be broken by unexpected user behavior and that all financial calculations were strictly accurate.</p>
<p><strong>Validation Testing:</strong> Testing covered every single data entry form. Deliberate invalid inputs were typed into the boxes (e.g., words instead of numbers). The testing verified that the system successfully blocked these faulty entries and correctly displayed red inline error warnings prior to submitting anything to the backend database.</p>
<p><strong>Error Injection & Security Testing:</strong> Security testing purposefully fed expired JWT tokens or modified network request headers to test whether the backend authentication middlewares correctly expelled the session. The testing verified the system appropriately reacted strictly protecting authorized routes effectively by sending the user back to the login page safely.</p>
<p><strong>Manual End-to-End Workflow Testing:</strong> Extensive manual testing followed the complete operational lifecycle to trace a standard order (replicating exactly Phase 1 through Phase 6 as outlined in Section 4.3.4). Tests verified that the system accurately tracked the balance amount, correctly updated the financial Cashbook automatically, and successfully generated the final PDF invoice email without encountering any errors or calculation mistakes.</p>

<h2>4.5 Key Libraries and Justification</h2>
<p>Specific external code libraries were chosen to solve targeted technical problems safely:</p>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Prisma ORM:</strong> Prevents database crashing errors by performing compile-time type safety checks, ensuring that text is never saved where a number should go.</li>
    <li><strong>Bcryptjs:</strong> It applies an adaptive difficulty (cost factor of 10) so passwords remain completely unreadable and secure even if the database is accessed by hackers.</li>
    <li><strong>Nodemailer:</strong> Connects securely to external email services via SMTP. This ensures customers receive their important OTP codes and PDF invoices quickly.</li>
    <li><strong>Ant Design:</strong> Chosen specifically for the admin dashboard side because it provides ready-to-use, professional tables, pop-ups, and forms, saving extensive development time.</li>
    <li><strong>Tailwind CSS:</strong> Used on the customer side to style the web pages quickly using utility classes without writing long, messy external CSS files.</li>
    <li><strong>Axios:</strong> Used to connect React to the Node.js backend because it easily attaches the secure JWT login token to every single network request automatically via an interceptor script.</li>
</ul>

<h2>4.6 Core Business Logic and System Automations</h2>
<p>The following logic rules handle the unique and highly customized business operations of the KaviCakes platform securely in the backend controllers code.</p>

<h3>4.6.1 Authentication & Security</h3>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Multi-Role System:</strong> The system strictly supports ADMIN and CUSTOMER roles. The routing logic explicitly keeps their access completely separate.</li>
    <li><strong>Verified Registration:</strong> Users must verify their email via a 6-digit OTP before they can log in and place orders. This blocks fake robot accounts.</li>
    <li><strong>JWT Protection:</strong> Secured API routes require a valid signature token embedded within the Authorization header.</li>
    <li><strong>Admin Singleton:</strong> The system is configured at a code level to allow only one primary admin account for maximum security, centralizing business control.</li>
</ul>

<h3>4.6.2 Product & Pricing Engine</h3>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Variant Pricing:</strong> The system calculates the final price using this specific mathematical rule: <em>Final price = (Category Base Price * Size Multiplier) + Flavor Premium</em>.</li>
    <li><strong>Bulk Pricing:</strong> It implements a "Threshold" system. If a customer places an order with a quantity integer greater than the bulk limit threshold, a lower bulk price matrix is applied per unit automatically.</li>
    <li><strong>Availability Guard:</strong> The logic queries and checks <code>isAvailable</code> boolean flags on both the main cake product and the specific variants chosen before it allows the item into a shopping cart.</li>
</ul>

<h3>4.6.3 Order Lifecycle Logic</h3>
<p>These backend variables strictly govern systemic operations.</p>
<table>
    <tr>
        <th>State</th>
        <th>Description</th>
        <th>Guardrails / Business Rules</th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td><strong>NEW</strong></td>
        <td>Order created by customer.</td>
        <td>Loyalty Points are strictly capped at 30% of the total. An urgency fee is automatically applied if delivery is needed in less than 48 hours.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td><strong>CONFIRMED</strong></td>
        <td>Admin acknowledged the order.</td>
        <td>Triggers an automated "Order Confirmed" email to the customer using Nodemailer.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td><strong>PREPARING</strong></td>
        <td>Kitchen starts work.</td>
        <td><strong>Strict Guard:</strong> The Admin cannot forcefully start this stage unless the Advance (30%) or Full Payment is officially verified and approved in the database.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td><strong>READY</strong></td>
        <td>Cake is boxed and ready.</td>
        <td>Triggers a visual dashboard notification indicating the order is set for immediate pickup or delivery.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td><strong>DELIVERED</strong></td>
        <td>Customer received order.</td>
        <td>Closes the active order loop and automatically generates a PDF Invoice, sending it to the customer.</td>
    </tr>
</table>

<h3>4.6.4 Payment & Advance Logic</h3>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Bank Slip Verification:</strong> When a customer uploads a payment proof image via the checkout form, the order enters a specialized <code>PENDING_VERIFICATION</code> state so the admin can review the physical image slip manually to prevent fraud.</li>
    <li><strong>Balance Tracking:</strong> The system calculates the physical total using the formula <code>total = advanceAmount + balanceAmount</code>. If the admin manually edits the order items after checkout, the balance amount property is updated dynamically to reflect the outstanding payment.</li>
    <li><strong>Manual Collection:</strong> Admins can record "In-Person Cash" payments physically handed over the counter directly in the dashboard, which then securely routes and updates the daily internal cashbook totals immediately.</li>
</ul>

<h3>4.6.5 Loyalty Point System</h3>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Earning:</strong> Customers automatically earn exactly 1 loyalty point for every Rs. 100 spent on their subtotal.</li>
    <li><strong>Spending:</strong> Customers can freely redeem their existing point balance at the checkout stage on future orders to receive an instant numerical discount.</li>
    <li><strong>Safety Rule:</strong> Point redemption logic is strictly mathematically capped never to exceed 30% of the gross cart total value. This protects the bakery's profit margins.</li>
    <li><strong>Urgent Fee Deduction:</strong> Urgent custom orders containing a short processing deadline automatically trigger a secondary logic script that deducts an additional 500 points from the customer's existing balance acting as a priority penalty efficiently.</li>
</ul>

